UNDERSTANDING YOUR SITUATION
You're in a unique position as a 2-employee IT consulting company in New Jersey wanting to provide insurance for one employee with a family. This is actually more challenging than having a larger company because you have limited negotiating power, but there are definitely solutions available.
Your employee's current plan shows they have a PPO with a $3,000 individual deductible, $6,000 family deductible maximum, and 75-25 cost sharing with a 25% copay. The maximum out-of-pocket is $6,000. This is actually a moderate plan that provides decent protection against catastrophic costs.
YOUR OPTIONS IN NEW JERSEY
New Jersey defines a small employer as having between 1 and 50 employees, so you qualify for small group health insurance. However, there are important participation and contribution requirements you need to understand.
Option 1: Traditional Small Group Health Insurance
For small group insurance in New Jersey, you must meet a participation requirement where at least 75% of full-time employees working 25 or more hours per week must be covered either by your plan or by other qualifying coverage like Medicare, Medicaid, another group plan, or a spouse's plan. For contribution requirements, you're only required to pay a minimum of 10% of the total cost, though you can choose to pay more New Jersey Small Employer Health Benefits Law | Wilentz, Goldman & Spitzer, P.A..
With only 2 employees, this means if one employee opts out (perhaps they have coverage through a spouse), you can still offer coverage to the other employee and meet the 75% requirement since 50% would round up in most carrier interpretations, especially if the non-participating employee has alternative coverage.
Option 2: SHOP Marketplace (Small Business Health Options Program)
New Jersey offers SHOP plans through GetCoveredNJ, and if you qualify, you could receive a Small Business Health Care Tax Credit worth up to 50% of the premiums you pay for employees, or 35% for non-profit employers GetCoveredNJ | Small Employers/SHOP. To qualify for the full tax credit, you generally need fewer than 10 full-time employees paying average wages of $25,000 or less, but businesses with up to 25 employees earning less than $50,000 average salary may qualify for partial credits New Jersey Small Business Health Insurance - eHealth.
Option 3: Professional Employer Organization (PEO)
Some small businesses join PEOs to get the benefits of a large company, where multiple small businesses pool together under one umbrella, allowing the PEO to negotiate better rates with insurance providers than individual small companies could get on their own Health Care Costs Are a Nightmare for Small Businesses—and They're Going Up in 2025. This could be particularly helpful for a 2-person company.
Option 4: Individual Coverage Health Reimbursement Arrangement (ICHRA)
Instead of traditional group insurance, you could use an ICHRA, which allows you to reimburse employees for their individual health plan premiums and medical expenses on a pre-tax basis New Jersey Small Business Health Insurance - eHealth. This gives your employee complete freedom to choose their own plan while you control costs with a fixed monthly allowance.
