WellCare provides the cheapest health insurance in New Jersey with an average monthly premium of $430, though availability may vary by county Cheapest Health Insurance in New Jersey: Affordable Plans for 2025.
My Recommendation for Your Situation:
Given that your employee currently has a PPO plan and wants to maintain that flexibility, I would recommend you focus your negotiations on UnitedHealthcare, Horizon Blue Cross Blue Shield, or Aetna (for direct small group plans, not marketplace). These three carriers offer the best combination of PPO plan availability, network breadth, and service quality.
UNDERSTANDING PPO VS HMO OPTIONS
Your employee prefers a PPO plan, which is understandable. Let me explain the differences so you can make an informed decision:
PPO (Preferred Provider Organization):
Employees can see any doctor without referrals
Coverage available for out-of-network providers (though at higher cost)
More flexibility but generally higher premiums
Better for employees who want choice and have established relationships with specific doctors
Your employee's current plan is PPO, so they're familiar with this structure
HMO (Health Maintenance Organization):
Requires choosing a primary care physician (PCP)
Need referrals to see specialists
Generally only covers in-network care (except emergencies)
Lower premiums and out-of-pocket costs
Better for budget-conscious employees who don't mind the structure
EPO (Exclusive Provider Organization):
Middle ground between HMO and PPO
No referrals needed for specialists
But no out-of-network coverage except emergencies
Often more affordable than PPO
Common in New Jersey marketplace
Given your employee's preference and current PPO plan, you should primarily request PPO quotes, but also ask for EPO options as they may offer significant savings while maintaining much of the flexibility.
