Step 8: Negotiate (This is where you can make a real difference)
While small businesses with fewer than 50 employees that are fully insured generally cannot negotiate rates Small Business Health Insurance - Can You Negotiate Your Rates? - Small Business Health Insurance Brokers | Abbot Benefits Group, you still have leverage in several ways:
What You CAN Negotiate:
Employer Contribution Level: Start at 10% minimum and negotiate up to what you can afford (50-75% is competitive for small businesses)
Plan Design Modifications: Ask if you can adjust:
Deductible amounts (higher deductible = lower premium)
Coinsurance splits (80/20 vs 70/30)
Copay amounts
Adding or removing specific benefits
Broker Commission: Your broker earns commission. If you're comparing similar quotes, ask if they can reduce their commission to lower your premium by 1-2%.
Multi-Product Discounts: You already have general liability with Hiscox. Ask if bundling health insurance (if the carrier offers it) or adding dental/vision could reduce overall costs.
Wellness Program Credits: Some carriers offer premium reductions if you implement wellness programs. Ask about this.
Payment Terms: Annual payment vs monthly may offer discounts (typically 2-5%).
Negotiation Strategy:
Get at least 3 competitive quotes to show carriers
Tell each broker: "I have competitive quotes from [Carrier X] and [Carrier Y]. What can you do to match or beat this while maintaining comparable coverage?"
Use the broker as your negotiator - that's their expertise
Don't reveal your maximum budget initially
Ask: "What can you do to improve this quote?" rather than accepting the first offer
Phase 4: Understanding COBRA and Pre-Existing Conditions (Important Legal Information)
Your COBRA Questions Answered:
COBRA allows individuals to maintain their existing health insurance plan without exclusions or pre-existing condition limitations, ensuring access to medical care and prescriptions under the same coverage terms as the previous employer-sponsored plan COBRA Insurance | Continuation of Health Coverage.
However, there's critical information you need to know:
Federal COBRA only applies to private-sector employers with 20 or more employees COBRA Insurance | Continuation of Health Coverage. Since you only have 2 employees, you are NOT required to offer federal COBRA.
BUT: New Jersey has its own Small Employer Health Benefits (SEH) Program that includes a continuation right for employees and their dependents when they're no longer eligible for the group's health plan, and this continuation right applies even when an employer is not subject to federal COBRA NJDOBI | Small Employer Health Benefits Program (SEH).
Pre-Existing Conditions and New Coverage:
Here's the excellent news: Health insurance plans through an employer are ACA-certified and cover pre-existing conditions and include prescription medication benefits COBRA Insurance Cost in 2025 | How Much Is COBRA?. Under the Affordable Care Act (ACA), no insurance company can deny coverage or charge more based on pre-existing conditions for small group health insurance.
This means:
Your employee's family can enroll regardless of any medical conditions
There are no waiting periods for pre-existing conditions
The insurance company CANNOT deny coverage
Rates are based on age, location, and tobacco use only - NOT health status
If Your Employee Is Coming From COBRA:
If your employee is currently on COBRA from a previous employer and switches to your new group plan:
All pre-existing conditions are covered immediately
No gaps in coverage
The new plan must accept them
When COBRA coverage is exhausted, individuals may qualify for individual health insurance coverage as HIPAA-eligible individuals, which allows them to purchase individual health coverage on a guaranteed available basis with no exclusion period for preexisting medical conditions COBRA Continuation Coverage | CMS
Phase 5: Coverage for Children Who Are US Citizens
Important Information About Dependent Coverage:
All qualified health plans (including small group plans) must follow ACA requirements for dependent coverage:
Children must be offered coverage until age 26, regardless of:
Where they live
Whether they're married
Whether they're students
Whether they have access to other coverage
Their citizenship status
Citizenship does NOT affect coverage or pricing. Whether a child is:
Born in the US (US citizen)
Born outside the US but is a legal resident
Or has any other legal status
...the health insurance treats them the same. Rates for children are the same regardless of citizenship. The insurance company cannot ask about or discriminate based on citizenship status.
Family coverage typically includes:
The employee
The employee's spouse or domestic partner
All dependent children under 26
Pricing: Most carriers offer:
Employee Only
Employee + Spouse
Employee + Child(ren)
Family (Employee + Spouse + Children)
The "Family" rate covers all children regardless of number (whether you have 1 child or 5 children, same family rate).
