WHAT TO KNOW WHEN TALKING TO INSURANCE COMPANIES/BROKERS
Critical Questions to Ask:
About the Plan:
"What is the total monthly premium, and how does it break down between employer and employee contributions?"
"What is the actual provider network, and can you confirm [employee's doctors] are in-network?"
"What is the prescription drug formulary, and what tier are [specific medications if any]?"
"Are there any services subject to the deductible, or do some have copays before the deductible?"
"What is the process for prior authorizations and referrals?"
"Does this plan have any waiting periods for specific services?"
"What telemedicine options are included?"
About Costs:
8. "What is our total cost exposure if an employee has a major medical event (surgery, hospitalization)?"
9. "What rate increases should we expect at renewal?"
10. "Are there any fees beyond the premium (administration, enrollment, etc.)?"
11. "Do you offer rate guarantees for the first year?"
About Administration:
12. "What is the enrollment process timeline?"
13. "What ongoing administrative support do you provide?"
14. "How do we handle qualifying life events (new baby, marriage, etc.)?"
15. "What happens if we need to add the second employee mid-year?"
16. "What is the grace period for premium payments?"
About Compliance:
17. "Will you provide all required notices (Summary of Benefits, HIPAA, etc.)?"
18. "Do you assist with ACA reporting if we grow beyond 50 employees?"
19. "What are the participation requirements if we add employees?"
Red Flags to Watch For:
Brokers who only show you one carrier (they may have special incentives)
Promises of rates that seem too good to be true
Pressure to sign immediately without time to review
Unwillingness to provide written quotes
Vague answers about network or coverage details
Plans with extremely high deductibles but low premiums (may leave employee exposed)
