FINAL RECOMMENDATIONS FOR SUCCESS
Use Multiple Brokers: Get quotes from 2-3 different brokers. They may have access to different carriers or negotiate differently.
Focus on Total Cost, Not Just Premium: A plan with a $2,000/month premium and $2,000 deductible may cost less annually than a $1,700/month premium with $6,000 deductible if your employee uses healthcare regularly.
Prioritize Network Over Price: If your employee has established doctors they want to keep, ensure those doctors are in-network. Otherwise, they'll face much higher costs or need to switch providers.
Start the Process Early: Allow 4-6 weeks before your desired effective date. Don't wait until you need coverage immediately.
Consider Future Growth: Even though you're covering one employee now, choose a plan that will work well if you add employees later.
Review Annually: Don't just auto-renew. Shop the market every year during renewal season. Rates and options change significantly.
Document Everything: Keep copies of all quotes, applications, and correspondence. You'll need these for tax purposes and future reference.
Consider Professional Help: Given the complexity and your small size, the $2,000-5,000 you might spend on a benefits consultant or PEO could save you more than that in better rates and avoiding mistakes.
While I cannot guarantee a "100% success rate" since insurance markets vary and individual circumstances differ, following this comprehensive approach will maximize your chances of securing excellent, affordable coverage for your employee. The key is to be thorough, compare multiple options, use brokers effectively, and focus on total value rather than just the lowest premium.
