Action two: Ask the broker these specific questions: "What is the typical approval timeline for a two-person group with your carrier? Who is the underwriter assigned to my application? What is the best way to check status daily? What could potentially delay approval?"
Action three: Tell the broker explicitly: "I need daily status updates because of the tight timeline. Can you commit to emailing me every day even if the status is just 'still processing'?" Get their commitment.
Action four: Research Rajesh's continuation coverage options from his current insurance as a backup plan. Find out the cost and deadline to elect it.
Action five: Set daily calendar reminders at 9 AM to contact your broker for status updates every day until approval.
October 10th through 13th - Active Monitoring
Every single day during this period, complete these actions:
Morning action: Call or email broker by 10 AM asking for status update. Document the response.
If any issues arise: Call the broker immediately when they notify you of a problem. Ask what information they need and provide it within one hour if possible. Common requests include: business formation documents, tax ID verification letter, prior insurance information, or clarification on participation requirements.
Wednesday October 13th checkpoint: If you don't have strong indication of imminent approval by end of day Wednesday, call the broker and say "I'm concerned about the timeline. What can we do to expedite this? Can you escalate to a manager or contact the carrier's expedite desk?" Be insistent but professional.
October 14th through 17th - Approval and Setup
When the broker calls to say you're approved, immediately do the following:
Action one: Ask for the policy number, coverage effective date confirmation of November 1st, total monthly premium amount, and billing instructions.
Action two: Set up the billing the same day you receive approval. If they offer automatic bank draft, set it up immediately with your business bank account information.
Action three: Ask about insurance cards. Request digital or temporary cards that can be emailed or faxed if physical cards will take more than one week to arrive.
Action four: Request the broker email you all of these documents by end of day: policy declarations page, schedule of benefits, summary of benefits and coverage, insurance carrier customer service contact information, and broker contact information for future questions.
Action five: As soon as you receive the policy documents, forward them to Rajesh with a note saying "Your new insurance is approved and starts November 1st. I'll schedule a call to walk you through everything."
October 18th through 20th - Employee Communication
Action one: Schedule a forty-five minute call or in-person meeting with Rajesh to review the insurance coverage.
Action two: During this meeting, walk through each document explaining what's covered, how to use the insurance card, how to find in-network doctors using the carrier's website, what to do in an emergency, how to get prescriptions filled, and what costs he's responsible for versus what insurance covers.
Action three: Show Rajesh how to create an online account with the insurance carrier where he can view his coverage, download digital insurance cards, and track claims.
Action four: Set up the payroll deduction for Rajesh's portion of the premium. Calculate the per-paycheck amount and notify him in writing of the deduction amount and start date.
Action five: Give Rajesh all broker contact information and encourage him to call with any questions.
October 21st through 30th - Final Verification
Action one around October 25th: Call the insurance company directly using the customer service number on the policy documents. Verify that coverage is active in their system for November 1st. Give them your policy number and ask them to confirm the effective date and list all covered family members.
Action two: Have Rajesh contact his current insurance around October 27th to confirm his coverage ends October 31st and ask about any final claims or coordination.
Action three when physical insurance cards arrive: Have Rajesh verify all information is correct on the cards. If there are any errors, contact the broker immediately.
Action four: Have Rajesh take photos of all insurance cards and save them on his phone for easy access.
November 1st - Coverage Begins
If Rajesh needs to use the insurance immediately, he should call the customer service number on his card to verify coverage is active before going to a doctor or pharmacy. Have him keep your number and the broker's number handy in case any issues arise during the first week.
PART SIX: YOUR EMERGENCY BACKUP PLANS
If despite all efforts you're running behind schedule, here are your specific backup actions.
If by October 18th you don't have approval:
Immediately call Rajesh and tell him to prepare to elect continuation coverage from his current plan. In New Jersey, he has rights to continue his current coverage even if his employer has fewer than twenty employees. The cost will be the full premium plus up to two percent administrative fee, which might be $2,000 to $3,000 per month, but it prevents a coverage gap.
Also immediately contact Justworks at 1-888-534-1711 and tell them you need emergency enrollment. PEOs can sometimes provide coverage faster than traditional carriers.
If by October 25th you still don't have approval:
This is crisis mode. Have Rajesh immediately elect continuation coverage for at least one month. This ensures coverage November 1st even if expensive. Continue working on the permanent solution but you've now protected against the gap.
Simultaneously, escalate with your broker by calling their manager or supervisor and explaining the situation. Request they contact the insurance carrier's executive customer service team.
